snippet.textDisplay:
"So far the government has been trying to contain the virus by testing and isolating those infected" This is not true. Please stop perpetuating a lie. Lies like this will go down in history as fact, if not challenged, scrutinised and discussed. As of 2 days ago, only people who had travelled back from danger zones or had contact with... were of interest to 111. Those who had the exact symptoms of COVID-19, (and I do not mean to exaggerated common cold, but clear clinical symptoms), but had no 'travel contact' were told they did not need to call 111. Many not tested = figures artificially low. Lower figures = the appearance of containing the virus spread.



(Timestamp 14:22) Quote: "One strategy is, you can stamp out every case in the world...you've stopped that epidemic without achieving herd immunity, but you must get every single case in the world. With a mild disease, that's incredibly difficult *that's the phase we were in when we were trying to do containment and everbody else was trying to do containment, trying to stamp out every single case in the world...*" John Edmunds Prof of Epidemiology from LSHTM.


The UK was NOT willing to count likely community cases during the containment phase. Therefore, this line and the Government line and doubtless the one which will be written in the history books is untrue.


GPs (via telephone appointments), who suspected their patients may have had COVID-19 have been powerless to get their patients tested. GPs have been advised by PHE to tell their patients to use the online 111 service, (which filtered many out as previously mentioned). Don't forget, those who thought they may have the symptoms were (and still are) told to NOT go to a pharmacy, hospital or GP, obviously a sensible measure, but there was no assistance offered online 111 either, which left them in limbo, scared for themselves, their families and worried that they may have spread the virus further.

Some had been lead into a false sense of security by the 111 criteria and assumed this meant they were not at risk to others and went about their business, potentially spreading the virus. Others extremely worried, felt they had no option but to call 111 putting a burden on the system and STILL coming away with the same 'you do not fit the criteria for testing' line. It is critical to note, there was no other advice given, no signposting and no 'potential cases' register.

Essentially, many people were left to their own devices to make their own decisions on what they may or may not have. Many chose to believe their symptoms could surely not be COVID-19, because of the steering by 111. "Surely I would have been tested if 'they' thought I really did have it?" For some, decisions to carry on as normal were based on their mild symptoms, and perhaps more in hope or for some, decisions were based on convenience.

The point is, as many were NOT offered advice or testing, or registered on a potential list, people made their own decisions. It is obvious some chose to carry on as normal, potentially spreading the virus throughout the community.

snippet.textDisplay: If you’re fit and well, get out there and catch it, then self isolate for a month, then you’ll be able to get on with your life if you don’t die which you probably won’t.  All that will happen if you shut down society is that you’ll spread out the instances of the really serious cases.  The cost benefit analysis really doesn’t stack up.  If I was old and sick I’d stay indoors for a year.  I understand the emotional lad but the professor knows what he’s talking about; the UK 🇬🇧 have the best approach by far
